{
  "What type of symbiosis benefits BOTH organisms in the relationship?": "",
  "Predation": "",
  "Parasitism": "",
  "Commensalism": "",
  "Mutualism": "",
  "Mutualism is a symbiotic relationship in which both organisms benefit. Classic examples include clownfish and sea anemones, and mycorrhizal fungi with plant roots.": "",
  "In parasitism, which organism is harmed by the interaction?": "",
  "The parasite": "",
  "Neither organism": "",
  "Both organisms equally": "",
  "The host": "",
  "In parasitism, the parasite benefits at the expense of the host. The host organism is harmed through loss of nutrients, tissue damage, or disease, while the parasite gains resources for survival and reproduction.": "",
  "What is the term for a close, long-term biological interaction between two different species?": "",
  "Metabolism": "",
  "Homeostasis": "",
  "Symbiosis": "",
  "Photosynthesis": "",
  "Symbiosis refers to any long-term, close ecological relationship between two or more different species. The three main types of symbiosis are mutualism, commensalism, and parasitism.": "",
  "In a predator-prey relationship, what typically happens to prey populations when predator numbers increase?": "",
  "Prey populations go extinct immediately": "",
  "Prey populations decrease": "",
  "Prey populations are unaffected": "",
  "Prey populations increase": "",
  "Predator-prey populations are linked in cycles. When predator numbers rise, they consume more prey, causing the prey population to decline. As prey declines, predators also decline due to less food, eventually allowing prey numbers to recover.": "",
  "What type of symbiotic relationship exists when one organism benefits and the other is neither helped nor harmed?": "",
  "Competition": "",
  "Commensalism is a relationship where one organism benefits while the other is unaffected. Examples include barnacles on whales and cattle egrets following large herbivores to catch disturbed insects.": "",
  "What is competition between two DIFFERENT species called?": "",
  "Interspecific competition": "",
  "Intraspecific competition": "",
  "Interspecific competition occurs between members of different species that compete for the same limited resources, such as food, territory, or nesting sites.": "",
  "What is competition between members of the SAME species called?": "",
  "Intraspecific competition occurs within a single species. Examples include male elk competing for mates and plants of the same species competing for sunlight. It is often more intense than interspecific competition because organisms have identical resource needs.": "",
  "What is the process called when two interacting species evolve reciprocal adaptations in response to each other?": "",
  "Artificial selection": "",
  "Genetic drift": "",
  "Convergent evolution": "",
  "Coevolution": "",
  "Coevolution occurs when two species exert selection pressure on each other, resulting in reciprocal adaptations over time. The predator-prey arms race between cheetahs and gazelles is a classic example.": "",
  "A parasite that lives INSIDE its host's body is called a(n):": "",
  "Mutualist": "",
  "Decomposer": "",
  "Endoparasite": "",
  "Ectoparasite": "",
  "Endoparasites live inside the host body, such as tapeworms and malaria-causing Plasmodium. Ectoparasites live on the host's external surface, such as ticks, lice, and fleas.": "",
  "Which term describes a species whose impact on its ecosystem is disproportionately large relative to its abundance?": "",
  "Keystone species": "",
  "Invasive species": "",
  "Endemic species": "",
  "Pioneer species": "",
  "A keystone species plays a critical role in maintaining ecosystem structure and function despite not being the most abundant species. Removing a keystone species causes significant changes throughout the ecosystem.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes symbiosis?": "",
  "Competition for resources within the same species": "",
  "A close, long-term biological interaction between two or more different species": "",
  "A brief, one-time encounter between two organisms": "",
  "The process by which organisms decompose dead matter": "",
  "Symbiosis encompasses all close, long-term interspecific interactions including mutualism, commensalism, and parasitism. The term comes from the Greek words 'sym' (together) and 'bios' (life).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a predator-prey relationship?": "",
  "A relationship where both organisms benefit from the interaction": "",
  "An interaction where one organism lives on another without causing harm": "",
  "A relationship between members of the same species competing for mates": "",
  "An interaction in which one organism hunts, kills, and consumes another organism for energy": "",
  "Predation is a fundamental ecological interaction in which the predator benefits by gaining energy and nutrients while the prey is killed. Predation helps regulate prey populations and drives evolutionary adaptations in both species.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes competition in ecology?": "",
  "An interaction where one organism kills and eats another": "",
  "An interaction in which organisms vie for the same limited resources, reducing the fitness of both": "",
  "A relationship in which one organism benefits at the expense of another": "",
  "Competition occurs when organisms require the same limited resources such as food, territory, water, or mates. It can occur between different species (interspecific) or within the same species (intraspecific), and it negatively affects the fitness of both competitors.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes mutualism?": "",
  "An interaction where organisms compete for the same resources": "",
  "A symbiotic relationship in which both interacting organisms benefit": "",
  "A relationship where one organism benefits and the other is harmed": "",
  "A relationship where one organism benefits and the other is unaffected": "",
  "Mutualism is a type of symbiosis where both partners gain fitness benefits from the interaction. Examples include pollinators and flowering plants, and mycorrhizal fungi with plant roots.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes parasitism?": "",
  "An interaction where a predator kills and immediately consumes prey": "",
  "A relationship in which both organisms benefit equally": "",
  "A symbiotic relationship in which one organism benefits at the expense of another organism, the host": "",
  "Parasitism is a relationship where the parasite gains resources from the host, harming but typically not immediately killing it. Unlike predation, parasites maintain a long-term relationship with their host to continue exploiting it.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes commensalism?": "",
  "A relationship in which both organisms benefit from the interaction": "",
  "A symbiotic relationship in which one organism benefits while the other is neither helped nor harmed": "",
  "An interaction in which both organisms are negatively affected": "",
  "A relationship in which one organism benefits and the other is harmed": "",
  "Commensalism is symbolized as (+/0), meaning one organism benefits and the other is unaffected. Examples include epiphytic orchids growing on tree branches and barnacles attaching to whales for transport.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes coevolution?": "",
  "The process by which two interacting species evolve reciprocal adaptations in response to selection pressures from each other": "",
  "Random changes in allele frequency within a population": "",
  "Two unrelated species independently evolving similar traits": "",
  "Humans selectively breeding organisms for desired characteristics": "",
  "Coevolution produces escalating adaptations between interacting species, often described as an evolutionary arms race. The rough-skinned newt and garter snake toxin-resistance system is a well-documented example.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a vector in ecology?": "",
  "A species that benefits from living inside another organism": "",
  "An organism that competes with its host for food": "",
  "An organism that transmits a pathogen or parasite from one host to another": "",
  "An organism that decomposes dead organic material": "",
  "Vectors are typically arthropods like mosquitoes, ticks, or fleas that transmit disease-causing organisms between hosts. Anopheles mosquitoes are vectors for malaria-causing Plasmodium parasites.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes obligate mutualism?": "",
  "Competition between two species for the same resource": "",
  "A mutualistic relationship in which neither partner can survive or reproduce without the other": "",
  "A mutualism where both organisms can survive independently": "",
  "In obligate mutualism, both partners are completely dependent on each other. Leaf-cutter ants and their cultivated fungus are a classic example — neither can survive without the other.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the competitive exclusion principle?": "",
  "The idea that competition always leads to extinction of both species": "",
  "The principle that predators always exclude prey from an ecosystem": "",
  "The principle that two species competing for identical resources cannot coexist indefinitely in the same habitat": "",
  "The idea that all symbiotic relationships eventually become parasitic": "",
  "The competitive exclusion principle (Gause's law) states that when two species occupy identical niches, one will inevitably outcompete and displace the other. The displacement of red squirrels by gray squirrels in England is a well-known example.": "",
  "A marine biologist observes clownfish living among sea anemone tentacles. The anemone's stinging cells protect the clownfish, while the clownfish's waste provides nutrients for the anemone. When separated experimentally, both species show reduced fitness. This relationship is BEST classified as:": "",
  "Commensalism — only the clownfish benefits from the interaction": "",
  "Parasitism — the clownfish harms the anemone": "",
  "Mutualism — both species receive measurable benefits from the interaction": "",
  "Predation — the anemone captures the clownfish": "",
  "This is a classic mutualism. The clownfish gains protection from predators through immunity to the anemone's nematocysts, while the anemone benefits from nitrogen-rich waste, increased water circulation, and defense against butterfly fish. The reduced fitness of both when separated confirms the mutual benefit.": "",
  "A veterinarian discovers a 3-meter tapeworm in a patient's intestine. The tapeworm has been absorbing nutrients from digested food, causing malnutrition and weight loss. Unlike a tick that feeds externally, this organism lives INSIDE the body. It is classified as:": "",
  "A decomposer — it breaks down dead tissue": "",
  "An ectoparasite — a parasite living on the external surface": "",
  "An endoparasite — a parasite that lives inside the host's body": "",
  "A mutualist — both the tapeworm and human benefit": "",
  "Parasites are classified by location: endoparasites (tapeworms, Plasmodium) live inside the host, while ectoparasites (ticks, lice, fleas) live on the exterior. Endoparasites often have complex life cycles involving multiple hosts and can grow to remarkable sizes inside the host body.": "",
  "After gray squirrels were introduced to England, red squirrel populations declined by 85%. Both species feed on acorns and nest in tree cavities. Gray squirrels are larger, tolerate higher tannin levels, and carry squirrelpox virus that is fatal to reds but harmless to grays. This BEST demonstrates:": "",
  "Predation — gray squirrels hunting red squirrels": "",
  "Interspecific competition with competitive exclusion — the gray squirrel occupies the same niche more effectively": "",
  "Commensalism — gray squirrels benefit while reds are unaffected": "",
  "Intraspecific competition — members of the same species competing": "",
  "This is interspecific competition leading to competitive exclusion. Gray squirrels outcompete reds through multiple advantages: larger body size, ability to digest higher-tannin acorns, and carrying squirrelpox. The competitive exclusion principle predicts that two species with identical niches cannot coexist indefinitely.": "",
  "Mycorrhizal fungi connect 90% of forest trees through underground networks dubbed the 'Wood Wide Web.' Trees share nutrients and chemical warning signals through this network, while fungi receive 10-30% of the trees' photosynthetic carbon. When the network is disrupted, tree growth and survival decline. This relationship is:": "",
  "Mutualism — trees gain water and mineral absorption while fungi receive organic carbon": "",
  "Parasitism — the fungi are stealing carbon from the trees": "",
  "Commensalism — only the fungi benefit from the network": "",
  "Competition — trees and fungi compete for soil nutrients": "",
  "Mycorrhizal fungi form arguably the most important mutualism on Earth. The fungal network vastly extends root absorption capacity (up to 1,000% increase in mineral uptake), while receiving photosynthetic sugars. The interconnected network also allows trees to share resources and communicate chemical alarm signals when under pest attack.": "",
  "Common cuckoo eggs closely mimic their host's eggs in color and pattern. Over evolutionary time, hosts evolved better detection of foreign eggs, and cuckoos counter-evolved more convincing mimicry. The cuckoo chick hatches first and pushes host eggs out, destroying the host's entire brood. This illustrates:": "",
  "Mutualism — both the cuckoo and host benefit from egg sharing": "",
  "Commensalism — the host is unaffected by the cuckoo's presence": "",
  "Brood parasitism driving a coevolutionary arms race between parasite and host": "",
  "Convergent evolution — both species independently evolved similar eggs": "",
  "Brood parasitism is a specialized form of parasitism where the cost to the host is its entire reproductive output. The escalating egg mimicry by cuckoos and improved detection by hosts exemplifies a coevolutionary arms race that has produced remarkable adaptations.": "",
  "Oxpeckers were long classified as mutualists with rhinoceroses — eating ticks from their skin. However, recent studies reveal oxpeckers also peck at wounds to drink blood, slowing healing. Rhinos with oxpeckers actually have MORE open wounds than those without. How does this change the classification?": "",
  "The relationship is context-dependent — it falls on a spectrum between mutualism and parasitism depending on net effects": "",
  "No ecological relationship exists between the two species": "",
  "Pure predation — the oxpecker is killing the rhino": "",
  "Pure commensalism — the rhino is completely unaffected": "",
  "This case illustrates that symbiotic relationships exist on a continuum and can shift depending on conditions. The net effect — which varies by context, season, and host condition — determines the true classification. Many textbook mutualisms turn out to be more complex when studied in detail.": "",
  "The rough-skinned newt produces tetrodotoxin (TTX), one of nature's deadliest toxins. Garter snakes in the same region have evolved TTX resistance, but at a cost — reduced crawling speed. In areas without newts, snakes have zero resistance. This geographic variation demonstrates:": "",
  "Mutualism — both species benefit from the toxin-resistance system": "",
  "Artificial selection — humans bred snakes for resistance": "",
  "A coevolutionary arms race creating a geographic mosaic of local adaptations": "",
  "Convergent evolution — newts and snakes independently evolved the same trait": "",
  "The Brodie & Brodie newt-snake system is a textbook coevolutionary arms race. Where newts are highly toxic, snakes have high resistance (at a locomotion cost). Where newts are absent, snakes lack resistance. This geographic mosaic shows how selection pressures vary across ranges, creating hotspots of local adaptation.": "",
  "At a coral reef cleaning station, a cleaner wrasse eats parasites from the gills and mouth of a large grouper. The grouper opens its jaws without eating the wrasse. When researchers observe the wrasse eating healthy mucus instead of parasites, the grouper jerks and swims away. What does this 'cheating and punishment' dynamic reveal?": "",
  "The relationship is purely parasitic — the wrasse only exploits clients": "",
  "Mutualism can be maintained by behavioral enforcement — cheating is deterred by client punishment": "",
  "The relationship is commensalism — only the wrasse benefits": "",
  "The grouper is preying on the wrasse": "",
  "Cleaning symbiosis demonstrates that mutualism requires mechanisms to prevent exploitation. When wrasses cheat by eating mucus, clients punish them by leaving — reducing future food supply. Studies show reefs without cleaner wrasses have significantly higher parasite loads and lower fish diversity.": "",
  "After wolves were reintroduced to Yellowstone in 1995, coyote populations declined. This actually benefited rodents and rabbits that coyotes had been suppressing. Meanwhile, wolves and coyotes compete for overlapping prey like elk calves. This cascade demonstrates:": "",
  "Commensalism — coyotes are unaffected by wolf presence": "",
  "Mutualism between wolves and coyotes": "",
  "Parasitism — wolves live as parasites on coyotes": "",
  "Interspecific competition combined with mesopredator release — wolves suppress coyotes, indirectly benefiting smaller prey": "",
  "Wolves are both competitors and intraguild predators of coyotes. Wolf reintroduction reduced coyote densities, which released smaller prey from coyote predation — a mesopredator release in reverse. This shows how interspecific competition at one trophic level can restructure entire food webs.": "",
  "Leaf-cutter ants harvest leaf fragments to cultivate a specific fungus in underground gardens. The fungus cannot survive without ant-provided substrate, and the ants cannot digest leaves without the fungus. The ants also carry Pseudonocardia bacteria that produce antibiotics to protect the fungus from parasitic mold. What type of relationship is this three-way system?": "",
  "Competition — the three species compete for leaf nutrients": "",
  "Parasitism — the ants exploit the fungus for food": "",
  "Obligate mutualism — all three organisms depend on each other and cannot survive independently": "",
  "Commensalism — the bacteria benefit while the others are unaffected": "",
  "Leaf-cutter ants pioneered agriculture ~50 million years before humans. This obligate mutualism involves three partners: ants provide substrate and protection, the fungus converts cellulose to digestible nutrients, and Pseudonocardia bacteria produce antibiotics against parasitic Escovopsis mold. None can survive without the others.": ""
}